.TH snmpa_local_db 3 "snmp 5.20.1" "Ericsson AB" "Erlang Module Definition"
.SH NAME
snmpa_local_db \- The SNMP built-in database

.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
The module \fIsnmpa_local_db\fR contains functions for implementing tables (and variables) using the SNMP built-in database. The database exists in two instances, one volatile and one persistent. The volatile database is implemented with ets. The persistent database is implemented with dets.

.PP
There is a scaling problem with this database.


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
Insertions and deletions are inefficient for large tables.

.RE

.PP
This problem is best solved by using Mnesia instead.

.PP
The following functions describe the interface to \fIsnmpa_local_db\fR. Each function has a Mnesia equivalent. The argument \fINameDb\fR is a tuple \fI{Name, Db}\fR where \fIName\fR is the symbolic name of the managed object (as defined in the MIB), and \fIDb\fR is either \fIvolatile\fR or \fIpersistent\fR. \fImnesia\fR is not possible since all these functions are \fIsnmpa_local_db\fR specific.

.SS "Common Data Types"

.PP
In the functions defined below, the following limitation applies:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIDb = volatile | persistent\fR

.RE

.PP
\fBSee Also\fR

.PP
ets(3), dets(3), snmp_generic(3)

.SH FUNCTIONS
.LP
.B
\fBdump() -> ok | {error, Reason} when Reason :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
This function can be used to manually dump the database to file.


.RE
.B
\fBmatch(Table, Pattern) -> [Match]\fR
\fB               when\fR
\fB                   Table :: snmpa:name_db() | snmpa:name(),\fR
\fB                   Pattern :: ets:match_pattern(),\fR
\fB                   Match :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Performs an ets/dets matching on the table.

.PP
See \fIets:match/2\fR for a description of \fIPattern\fR and the return values.


.RE
.B
\fBprint(Table, Db) -> term()\fR
\fB               when Table :: snmpa:name(), Db :: volatile | persistent.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Prints the contents of the database on screen. This is useful for debugging since the \fISTANDARD-MIB\fR and \fIOTP-SNMPEA-MIB\fR (and maybe your own MIBs) are stored in \fIsnmpa_local_db\fR.

.PP
\fITable\fR is an atom for a table in the database. When no name is supplied, the whole database is shown.

.PP
Note that these functions does not actually print, using io:format/2, instead they (just) return the information. If executed in a shell, the information will then be displayed (probably truncated) there.

.PP
A better use would be:

.IP
.nf
	  io:format("~p~n", [snmpa_local_db:print()]).

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBtable_create(Table) -> boolean()\fR
\fB                      when Table :: snmpa:name_db() | snmpa:name().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Creates a table. If the table already exist, the old copy is destroyed.

.PP
Returns \fIfalse\fR if the \fINameDb\fR argument is incorrectly specified, \fItrue\fR otherwise.

.PP
Database (only table name specified) defaults to \fIvolatile\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBtable_create_row(Table, RowIndex, Row) -> boolean()\fR
\fB                          when\fR
\fB                              Table :: snmpa:name_db() | snmpa:name(),\fR
\fB                              RowIndex :: snmp:row_index(),\fR
\fB                              Row :: tuple().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Creates a row in a table. \fIRow\fR is a tuple with values for all columns, including the index columns.

.PP
Database (only table name specified) defaults to \fIvolatile\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBtable_delete(Table) -> true\fR
\fB                      when Table :: snmpa:name_db() | snmpa:name().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Deletes a table.

.PP
Database (only table name specified) defaults to \fIvolatile\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBtable_delete_row(Table, RowIndex) -> boolean()\fR
\fB                          when\fR
\fB                              Table :: snmpa:name_db() | snmpa:name(),\fR
\fB                              RowIndex :: snmp:row_index().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Deletes the row in the table.

.PP
Database (only table name specified) defaults to \fIvolatile\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBtable_exists(Table) -> boolean()\fR
\fB                      when Table :: snmpa:name_db() | snmpa:name().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Checks if a table exists.

.PP
Database (only table name specified) defaults to \fIvolatile\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBtable_get_element(Table, RowIndex, Col) ->\fR
\fB                           {value, Value} | undefined\fR
\fB                           when\fR
\fB                               Table :: snmpa:name_db() | snmpa:name(),\fR
\fB                               RowIndex :: snmp:row_index(),\fR
\fB                               Col :: snmp:column(),\fR
\fB                               Value :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Get a column value (element) from a row of the table.

.PP
Database (only table name specified) defaults to \fIvolatile\fR.

.PP
This function has existed for long time, but not had a proper since tag, so to simplify we set the since tag to when it was documented.


.RE
.B
\fBtable_get_row(Table, RowIndex) -> Row | undefined\fR
\fB                       when\fR
\fB                           Table :: snmpa:name_db() | snmpa:name(),\fR
\fB                           RowIndex :: snmp:row_index(),\fR
\fB                           Row :: tuple().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
\fIRow\fR is a tuple with values for all columns, including the index columns.

.PP
Database (only table name specified) defaults to \fIvolatile\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBtable_set_elements(Table, RowIndex, Cols) -> boolean()\fR
\fB                            when\fR
\fB                                Table :: snmpa:name_db() | snmpa:name(),\fR
\fB                                RowIndex :: snmp:row_index(),\fR
\fB                                Cols :: [{Col, Value}],\fR
\fB                                Col :: snmp:column(),\fR
\fB                                Value :: term().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Update the specified columnar objects of the row of this table.

.PP
Database (only table name specified) defaults to \fIvolatile\fR.

.PP
This function has existed for long time, but not had a proper since tag, so to simplify we set the since tag to when it was documented.


.RE
